Here’s a clear breakdown of each mode code in your dataset, based on standard transit classifications (commonly from U.S. transit data like the National Transit Database):

⸻

🚍 Bus & Road-Based Modes
	•	DR — Demand Response
Flexible, on-demand service (paratransit, dial-a-ride). No fixed routes or schedules.
	•	MB — Motor Bus
Standard city buses running on fixed routes and schedules.
	•	CB — Commuter Bus
Longer-distance buses connecting suburbs to urban centers (often peak-hour focused).
	•	RB — Bus Rapid Transit (BRT)
Bus system with dedicated lanes, priority signals, and faster service.
	•	TB — Trolleybus
Electric buses powered by overhead wires.
	•	PB — Publico / Público
Shared-ride vans or jitneys operating on semi-fixed routes (common in places like Puerto Rico).

⸻

🚆 Rail Modes
	•	LR — Light Rail
Electric trains, usually street-level or partially separated (e.g., trams).
	•	HR — Heavy Rail
High-capacity metro/subway systems with full separation from traffic.
	•	SR — Streetcar Rail
Rail vehicles running mostly in mixed traffic on city streets.
	•	CR — Commuter Rail (not listed but often confused with CB)
Regional passenger trains connecting suburbs to cities.

⸻

🚐 Specialized / Flexible Transit
	•	VP — Vanpool
Shared vans for commuters, typically organized by employers or groups.
	•	IP — Inclined Plane
Cable-powered rail systems on steep slopes (funiculars).
	•	MG — Monorail / Automated Guideway
Rail systems running on a single beam or automated tracks.
	•	YR — Hybrid Rail (e.g., “Hybrid Rail” or similar category)
Rail systems combining characteristics of light and commuter rail (diesel/electric mix).

⸻

🚢 Water Transport
	•	FB — Ferryboat
Passenger boats operating on rivers, bays, or coastal routes.

⸻

🚠 Cable / Unique Systems
	•	CC — Cable Car
Rail cars pulled by continuously moving underground cables (e.g., San Francisco-style).
	•	TR — Aerial Tramway
Cable-suspended cars traveling through the air (like gondolas).

⸻

✈️ Other / Rare Modes
	•	JT — Jitney
Informal or semi-formal shared ride service (very rare in your dataset).

⸻

🧠 Key Takeaways
	•	Most common:
	•	DR (Demand Response)
	•	MB (Motor Bus)
	•	Rail systems: LR, HR, SR are smaller but structured transit
	•	Niche modes: JT, CC, TR, IP appear rarely and are highly specialized

